'''Carlsberg Architectural Prize''' ({{lang-da|Carlsberg Arkitekturpris}}) was an [[:Category:Architecture awards|architecture award]] founded by the Danish [[Carlsberg Foundation|New Carlsberg foundation]] in 1991.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.carlsberggroup.com/Investor/DownloadCentre/Shared%20Documents/Annual%20Report/AnnualReport9798UK.pdf|title=Carlsberg Group: Annual Report|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=15|via=|access-date=2016-07-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305035348/http://www.carlsberggroup.com/Investor/DownloadCentre/Shared%20Documents/Annual%20Report/AnnualReport9798UK.pdf#|archive-date=2016-03-05|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> It was awarded three times between the years 1992-1998 “To recognize excellence in lasting architectural design”.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_nVsqM5NxEYC|title=Felder's Comprehensive, 2005 Edition: The Annual Desk Reference and Product Thesaurus for Architects, Contractors, Engineers, and Interior Designers|last=Felder|first=Nick|date=2005-07-14|publisher=Princeton Architectural Press|isbn=9781568984742|language=en}}</ref> [[Margrethe II of Denmark|Her Majesty The Queen of Denmark]] acted as the patron of the prize. At the time of its foundation in 1991 the prize, being worth $235,000 was the biggest in the field of architecture.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/04/16/arts/tadao-ando-architect-wins-235000-prize.html|title=Tadao Ando, Architect, Wins $235,000 Prize|date=1992-04-16|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=2016-07-16}}</ref> The first recipient, Tadao Ando, donated the prize money for the Osaka Prefectural Government, later used to establish the Ando Fund administered by the Osaka Foundation of International Exchange.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ofix.or.jp/english/training/aprogram/about.html|title=Osaka Foundation of International Exchange -About Ando Fund-|website=www.ofix.or.jp|access-date=2016-10-15}}</ref>
== Laureates == * 1992 - [[Tadao Ando]] * 1995 - [[Juha Leiviskä]] * 1998 - [[Peter Zumthor]]
